After optimizing the experimental conditions, the analytical performance of the as-prepared biosensors at different dilution ratios of target DNA fragments was recorded (Fig. 3
                        ). The recovered CYP707A1 product was quantified as 663 ng μL−1 by NanoDrop ND-1000 spectrophotometer, and was calculated as 4.1 μM according to its sequence composition. Therefore, the gradient diluted CYP707A1 DNA had concentrations (cSample
                        ) of 4.1 μM, 256 nM, 128 nM, 32 nM, 8 nM, 4 nM, 800 pM, 400 pM, 80 pM and 40 pM, correspond to diluting cIntial
                         to 1, 16, 32, 128, 512, 1024, 5120, 10240, 51,200 and 102,400 times, respectively. As can be seen from Fig. 3A, SWV response of the biosensor enhances accordingly as the concentration of the target DNA fragments increasing. It can be seen in Fig. 3B that the calibration plot exhibits good linear relationship between the SWV responses and the logarithm of target DNA concentrations ranging from 40 pM to 4.1 μM (the reciprocal of the dilution factor). The linear regression equation is I (μA) = 2.640 lg (cSample/cIntial
                        ) + 20.95 ( r
                        2 = 0.998) and the detection limit is estimated to be 13 pM (S/N = 3).
